Spring Framework Questions
Core Spring
What is the Spring Framework, and what are its key features?
Spring is a Java framework for developing enterprise applications. Key features:
Dependency Injection (DI) and IoC (Inversion of Control) container.
Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP).
Modularization with components like Spring Core, Spring MVC, Spring Data, etc.
What is Dependency Injection (DI) in Spring?
DI is a design pattern used to implement IoC by injecting object dependencies at runtime instead of hardcoding them.
Example: A bean's dependencies can be automatically resolved using the @Autowired annotation.
What are the different scopes of Spring beans?
Singleton (default): Single instance shared across the container.
Prototype: A new instance is created every time the bean is requested.
Request: HTTP request-scoped (web applications only).
Session: HTTP session-scoped (web applications only).
Application: Shared across the Servlet lifecycle.
WebSocket: Scoped to a WebSocket lifecycle.
What is the difference between @Component, @Service, @Repository, and @Controller in Spring?
All of these annotations are stereotypes that indicate a class is a bean.
@Component: Marks a generic Spring-managed component class.
@Service: Marks a service layer class.
@Repository: Specialization for DAO classes that also provide translation for persistence-related exceptions.
@Controller: Marks a class as a Spring MVC controller.
What is the purpose of @Primary and @Qualifier in Spring?
@Primary: Specifies the default bean to use when multiple candidates for autowiring are available.
@Qualifier: Used to specify which bean to wire when multiple beans of the same type exist.
What is the difference between ApplicationContext and BeanFactory in Spring?
BeanFactory: The basic IoC container for managing beans and their lifecycle.
ApplicationContext: An enhanced container offering additional features like internationalization, event publishing, and integration with other services.
Explain Spring AOP and its use cases.
Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP) allows you to inject cross-cutting concerns like logging, transactions, or security without modifying the core logic.
Key components:
Aspect: Modularized behavior (e.g., logging).
JoinPoint: A point in the execution (e.g., method invocation).
Advice: Action to take at a join point (e.g., @Before, @After).
Pointcut: Expression that selects specific join points.
Weaving: The process of applying aspects.
